<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5> at large • in large</xh5><p> <i>at large—</i>1. not in confinement or captivity: The suspect was not found, and was still <u>at large</u>, police said. 2. unemployed; without an occupation: Are you <u>at large</u> or have you any other occupation? 3. is used of people in general: Did the people <u>at large</u> approve of the government’s policy? 4. without definite aim; at random: A single stroke well aimed returns a better result than a score which are delivered <u>at large</u>. 5. at great length; in detail: My mother and I <u>talked at large</u> on the subject.</p><p> <i>in large</i>—(also: in the large) as a whole: Are they pledging allegiance to a piece of cloth rather than their family and neighbors: their community in small and <u>in large</u>?</p> </entry>
